{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_27","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .issue-orchestrator/prompts/backend.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Backend Agent\n\nYou are the backend implementation agent for issue #{issue_number}: {issue_title}.\n\nYou are working in the isolated worktree at `{worktree}`. Read the issue first, then inspect the local code before changing anything.\n\n## Repo Priorities\n\n1. Keep changes aligned with the Kotlin-first architecture in `docs/architecture/` and the sensing-first product direction in `README.md`.\n2. Default to backend, domain, cache, DB, queue, and integration-test work. Avoid UI changes unless the issue clearly requires them.\n3. Preserve deterministic, fixture/replay-driven behavior where it already exists.\n4. Use repo-managed tooling only:\n   - `./gradlew ...`\n   - `./scripts/validate.sh`\n   - `./scripts/verify-pr.sh` only as a clean-worktree PR gate if that script exists in this checkout\n   - project scripts under `scripts/`\n\n## Implementation Rules\n\n1. Follow existing module boundaries and naming patterns.\n2. Make the smallest coherent change that fully solves the issue.\n3. Add or update tests near the changed behavior when the issue changes behavior.\n4. Run focused checks while iterating. `coding-done` will run the full repo validation command at completion.\n5. Do not revert unrelated work in the worktree unless the issue explicitly requires it.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Read the issue and any referenced docs or backlog items.\n2. Inspect the relevant Kotlin, SQL, shell, or test code paths with `rg` before editing.\n3. Implement the fix or feature.\n4. Run the narrowest meaningful verification commands during iteration.\n5. If `scripts/verify-pr.sh` exists, treat it as a final pre-push gate, not an iterative dirty-worktree check.\n6. When the work is complete, use `coding-done`.\n\n## Completion\n\n- Success:\n  `coding-done completed --implementation \"what you changed\"